1Ô∏è‚É£ Introduction

Chain of Responsibility (CoR) ek Behavioral Design Pattern hai.

üëâ Jab system me multiple handlers ho jo ek request ko process kar sakte hain,
üëâ Aur hume pehle se nahi pata ho ki kaunsa handler request handle karega,

Tab hum Chain of Responsibility use karte hain.


2Ô∏è‚É£ Basic Problem (Without CoR)
Example: Logger System

Suppose hum ek logger bana rahe hain:

INFO

DEBUG

ERROR

WARNING

Without CoR, code kuch aisa hoga:

public void log(int level, String message) {
    if(level == 1) {
        // Info logic
    } else if(level == 2) {
        // Debug logic
    } else if(level == 3) {
        // Error logic
    }
}

3Ô∏è‚É£ Problems with Multiple if-else
‚ùå 1. Open-Closed Principle Break

Open-Closed Principle kehta hai:

Class should be closed for modification but open for extension.

Agar kal ko naya level add karna ho (e.g., WARNING),
to existing class modify karni padegi ‚Üí ‚ùå OCP break.


‚ùå 2. Code Not Modular

Sab behavior ek hi class me hai.

WHAT (log type ‚Äì info/debug/error)

HOW (kaise process karna hai ‚Äì alarm trigger, cloud storage, etc.)

Dono tightly coupled hain.


‚ùå 3. Tight Coupling Problem

Agar Debug me galti ho gayi aur object create hi na ho,
to Info aur Error bhi kaam nahi karenge.

Ek jagah bug ‚Üí pura system impact.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Core Idea of Chain of Responsibility

Concept = Linked List

Har handler ek node hota hai.

Har node ke paas:

Apna processing logic

Next handler ka reference

